This translates to finding the smallest \( n \) such that \( a_n > 500 \). The sequence is defined as \( a_1 = 1 \) and \( a_{n+1} = \left\lceil \sqrt{a_n^2 + 34} \right\rceil \). 1. Calculate the initial terms of the sequence: - \( a_1 = 1 \) - \( a_2 = \left\lceil \sqrt{1^2 + 34} \right\rceil = \left\lceil \sqrt{35} \right\rceil = 6 \) - \( a_3 = \left\lceil \sqrt{6^2 + 34} \right\rceil = \left\lceil \sqrt{70} \right\rceil = 9 \) - \( a_4 = \left\lceil \sqrt{9^2 + 34} \right\rceil = \left\lceil \sqrt{115} \right\rceil = 11 \) - \( a_5 = \left\lceil \sqrt{11^2 + 34} \right\rceil = \left\lceil \sqrt{155} \right\rceil = 13 \) - \( a_6 = \left\lceil \sqrt{13^2 + 34} \right\rceil = \left\lceil \sqrt{203} \right\rceil = 15 \) - \( a_7 = \left\lceil \sqrt{15^2 + 34} \right\rceil = \left\lceil \sqrt{259} \right\rceil = 17 \) - \( a_8 = \left\lceil \sqrt{17^2 + 34} \right\rceil = \left\lceil \sqrt{323} \right\rceil = 18 \) - \( a_9 = \left\lceil \sqrt{18^2 + 34} \right\rceil = \left\lceil \sqrt{358} \right\rceil = 19 \) - \( a_{10} = \left\lceil \sqrt{19^2 + 34} \right\rceil = \left\lceil \sqrt{395} \right\rceil = 20 \) 2. From \( a_{10} \) onwards, each term increases by 1: - \( a_{10} = 20 \) - \( a_{11} = 21 \) - \( a_{12} = 22 \) - \( a_{13} = 23 \) - \( \ldots \) - \( a_{n} = 20 + (n - 10) \) for \( n \geq 10 \) 3. Solve for \( n \) such that \( a_n > 500 \): - \( 20 + (n - 10) > 500 \) - \( n - 10 > 480 \) - \( n > 490 \) - The smallest integer \( n \) is 491. Thus, the least value of \( n \) such that \( a_n > 500 \) is \(\boxed{491}\).
